KFC, Subway and Taco Bell all retain their positions from 2024, ranking third, fourth, and fifth, respectively.

In other findings, Chick-fil-A has become the sector’s fastest-growing brand, with its value increasing 43% to $5.7 billion. Its increase was driven by strong financial performance and a more than five-point increase in its Brand Strength Index score to 89.4 out of 100.

U.S. brands continue to dominate the ranking, accounting for 20 of the top 25 most valuable restaurant brands. Outside the U.S., China is represented by Haidilao (brand value $3.6 billion billion) and Luckin Coffee ($1.7 billion), while Canada, the Philippines, and the U.K. each contribute one brand.

Methodology

Brand Finance calculates the values of brands using the Royalty Relief brand valuation approach. It involves estimating the likely future revenues that are attributable to a brand by calculating a royalty rate that would be charged for its use, to arrive at a ‘brand value’ understood as a net economic benefit that a brand owner would achieve by licensing the brand in the open market. For the complete methodology, click here.

Here is Brand Finance list of the World’s Most Valuable Restaurant Brands:

McDonald’s ($40.5 billion); Starbucks ($38.8 billion); KFC ($15.4 billion); Subway ($8.1 billion); Taco Bell ($6.9 billion); Tim Horton’s ($6.8 billion); Domino’s ($6.7 billion); Chick-fil-A ($5.7 billion); Wendy’s ($5.2 billion); and Pizza Hut ($4.8 billion).

