We crossed paths a few times in the beginning of our freshman year at Howard University, but never made a formal introduction. As fate would have it, Brandy’s next door neighbor in The Quad and I had been friends since high school. One night, I went to visit said friend (shoutout to Symmi), but she’d just made a late night run to McDonalds. I knocked on Brandy’s door and asked if she could hang out until she got back. Well, 30 minutes quickly turned into an amazing 8-hour conversation where we talked about everything under the sun and shared our first kiss. We crossed paths a few times in the beginning of our freshman year at Howard University, but never made a formal introduction. As fate would have it, Brandy’s next door neighbor in The Quad and I had been friends since high school. One night, I went to visit said friend (shoutout to Symmi), but she’d just made a late night run to McDonalds. I knocked on Brandy’s door and asked if she could hang out until she got back. Well, 30 minutes quickly turned into an amazing 8-hour conversation where we talked about everything under the sun and shared our first kiss.

We were inspired after connecting to “come out” to our families the summer after freshman year so that we could begin living more freely. Both coming from Black religious households Houston and New York, respectively, looking back don’t know why we thought it was a good idea, but it was the onset of a shift in family dynamics as we knew them. Being two femmes in the LGBTQ community, who don’t always “live out loud,” has often come with its own hang ups.

By the end of sophomore year, Joy had become a part of the multitude of first generation students that couldn’t afford to stay any longer. For the next two years after that, we’d try our hardest to make it work while Brandy stayed in school, Joy moved back home, and our families were boldly navigating their dismay. We’d break up after Brandy’s graduation because life and the pressure of family told us it was best and the phase should be over. We dated other people just to realize how imperfectly perfect and equally yoked we truly were.

I moved back to DC in 2012 and we started dating again as two young adults blocking out the noise, away from home. The following year, we moved in together and were getting settled in our careers and life. In 2014, while Joy was working at GWU, an LGBTQ couple was involved in a horrible incident. Unfortunately, one of the partners had a freak accident and passed away. He was completely estranged from his family at the time. Not only did they come and take his body, and misappropriate his identity, but most heartbreakingly, they banned his partner from any participation in services or even the right to say goodbye. Joy came home devastated, unable to shake that feeling. Gay marriage was just recently passed in D.C. and we said, “I do,” less than 30 days later.

